elements.content: Discrete dinuclear and polymeric heterometallic copper(II)−lanthanide(III) complexes have been synthesized upon variation of pH and characterized by X-ray diffraction analysis. Reactions of the ligand Htza (tetrazole-1-acetic acid) with copper(II) and lanthanide(III) salts gave dinuclear [CuLn(tza)4(H2O)5Cl] complexes at the low pH of 3.5 and 2D heterometallic coordination polymers with high-nuclearity [{Cu2(OH)2}2{Cu12Ln6(μ3-OH)24(Cl)1/2(NO3)1/2(tza)12(H2O)18}](NO3)9·8H2O (Ln = Gd or Nd) at a higher pH of 6.6. The acidity of the reaction solution can cause drastic changes in the structures of the products. In the dinuclear complexes, each pair of adjacent dinuclear molecules is linked through hydrogen bonds and π−π stacking interactions, and the whole structure is a hydrogen-bonded three-dimensional cubic net. In the coordination polymers, the connecting nodes are [Cu12Ln6] units, which are interconnected by [Cu2O2] units into two-dimensional structures. Magnetic studies exhibit the existence of weak exchange interactions between the CuII and LnIII ions bridged by carboxylate and hydroxy ligands.

Introduction

There has been growing interest in recent years in the design and synthesis of high-nuclearity complexes motivated by their fascinating structures and rich physical properties. In contrast, rational synthesis of multidimensional polymers involving heterometallic high-nuclearity clusters linked by organic ligands is still a challenge in chemistry, and the synthetic difficulties restrict further studies of their chemical and physical properties. In fact, homometallic 4f cluster-based coordination polymers7 and heterometallic 3d-4f cluster-based, especially high-nuclearity-based, coordination polymers are seldomly reported. In the field of heterometallic 3d-4f coordination chemistry, we reported  the synthesis and magnetic investigations of a series of discrete heterometallic CuII-LnIII (Ln = lanthanide) complexes using betaine (i.e. trimethylammonioacetate) and its derivatives in the past decade, demonstrating a crucial role of the reaction pH in the formation of these clusters. As an expansion of the synthetic strategy to develop 3d-4f complexes chemistry, we attempted to construct multidimensional arrays and networks containing highly aggregate clusters as nodes and hope to provide useful information for the novel structures. Among them, the unusual nanosized [Cu12Ln6] cores14 bridged by μ3-OH- and carboxylate groups attracted our interest in assembly of them into nanoscale cluster-based frameworks. Obviously, if the hanging monocarboxylate ligand could be replaced by an appropriate exo-bidentate ligand, a new synthetic approach may be established for interlinking of such nanosized clusters into higher dimensional networks with intriguing structural features and useful physical properties.

elements.content: We selected a multifunctional ligand, tetrazole-1-acetic acid (designated as Htza) with both carboxylate and tetrazole ends, to replace betaines (Scheme ). The employment of this ligand was found to generate dinuclear [CuLn(tza)4(H2O)5Cl] (Ln = Gd or Nd) complexes at a low pH of 3.5. According to our previous acidity control approach, we were then able to isolate unusual two-dimensional (2D) networks based on the nanosized clusters [{Cu2(OH)2}2{Cu12Ln6(μ3-OH)24(Cl)1/2(NO3)1/2(tza)12(H2O)18}](NO3)9·8H2O (Ln = Gd (2·Gd) or Nd (2·Nd)) by mixing CuCl2 and Ln(NO3)3 (Ln = Gd or Nd) at a higher pH of 6.6. We now report herein the synthesis, crystal structures, and magnetic properties of the neutral dinuclear complexes and the 2D networks based on the nanosized clusters.

The data collections were carried out on a Bruker SMART Apex CCD diffractometer using graphite-monochromated Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.710 73 Å) at 293 K by using frames of 0.3° oscillation (4.3 ≤ 2θ ≤ 60°). Absorption corrections were applied by using SADABS. The structures were solved with direct methods and refined by full-matrix least-squares techniques with the SHELXTL programs. The anions encapsulated at the cage of the octadecanuclear Cu12Ln6 cluster in 2·Gd or 2·Nd were refined to be half a Cl- and half a disordered NO3 - anion. Anisotropic thermal parameters were applied to all non-hydrogen atoms. The organic hydrogen atoms were generated geometrically (C−H 0.96 Å); the aqua hydrogen atoms were located from difference maps and refined with isotropic temperature factors. Description of Crystal Structures. The crystal structure of 1·Gd consists of a discrete neutral, dinuclear [CuGd(tza)4(H2O)5Cl] molecule. An ORTEP view of the dinuclear molecule is shown in Figure . Both the CuII and GdIII atoms are located on a crystallographic 4-fold axis. The CuII ion is coordinated by four carboxylate oxygen atoms at the basal plane [Cu(1)−O 1.967 Å] (Table ) and completed by a Cl- ion at the apical position [Cu(1)−Cl(1) 2.494 Å] to exhibit a square-pyramidal geometry. The GdIII ion is quadruply bridged to the CuII ion by four carboxylate bridges of tza ligands in syn−syn bridging modes [Gd(1)−O 2.4455(14) Å], giving rise to a “paddle-wheel” heterometallic dimer with the Cu···Gd distance of 3.777 Å. This neutral dinuclear structure is somewhat different from the well-known, symmetric “paddle-wheel” structures of copper(II) carboxylates as well as the rare examples of related dinuclear Cu−Ln complexes documented in the literature. Besides the four μ-carboxylate oxygen atoms, the GdIII ion is further coordinated by five aqua ligands [Gd(1)−O = 2.4207(14)−2.615(3) Å] to form nine-coordination, leading to a distorted monocapped square-antiprism, in which one square face consists of four aqua oxygen atoms [O(3), O(3A), O(3B), and O(3C)] whereas the other is defined by four carboxylate oxygen atoms [O(12), O(22), O(32), and O(42)] from the quadruple μ-carboxylate bridges. The dihedral angle between the square faces is ca. 58°.

elements.content: In 2·Nd and 2·Gd there are both heterometallic octadecanuclear Cu12Ln6 subunits and dinuclear Cu2(μ-OH)2 subunits. X-ray structural analysis reveals that 2·Nd and 2·Gd are isostructural and only minor geometric differences are found. Therefore, only the structure of 2·Gd is described here. The Cu12Gd6 subunit in a 4/m site symmetry, which is the highest symmetry among such kinds of octadecanuclear cores, is slightly different from those found in our previously prepared discrete complexes. In this octadecanuclear core, 6 GdIII ions are positioned at the vertexes of a regular octahedron and the 12 CuII ions are located at the midpoints of the 12 octahedral edges (Figure ). This Cu−Gd metal framework is interconnected by 24 similar μ3-OH ligands that are each linked to one GdIII ion (Gd−O 2.462(3)−2.475(3) Å) and two CuII ions (Cu−O 1.944(3)−1.992(3) Å); each Gd(μ3-OH)4 fragment is square-pyramidal, and each Cu(μ3-OH)4 fragment is square-planar. Each GdIII ion is nine-coordinated in a monocapped square-antiprismatic geometry. There are two types of GdIII coordination environments:  each of the four GdIII atoms at the equatorial plane of octahedron is coordinated by four O atoms from μ3-OH and three O atoms from three tza μ-carboxylate-O,O‘ ends and two aqua ligands, whereas each of the two GdIII ions at the apical positions is ligated by four O atoms from μ3-OH and five aqua ligand. Different from the previously reported discrete Cu12Ln6 clusters, two axial GdIII atoms at the octahedron are not ligated by the carboxylate group. Each CuII ion is ligated in a square-pyramidal geometry with four μ3-OH groups in the basal plane and one tza carboxylate oxygen atom at the apical position (Cu−O 2.317(4)−3.379(5) Å). In the Cu12Ln6 core, each pair of the adjacent Cu···Cu is linked by a single OH- group bridge with the Cu···Cu distances in the range 3.307(2)−3.407(2) Å. Each GdIII ion is linked to four adjacent CuII atoms by four μ3-OH bridges with the Cu···Gd separations of 3.489(1)−3.535(1) Å, and each pair of GdIII atoms in each edge of the octahedron is separated at distances of 7.02 Å. In the surrounding of the Cu12Ln6 core, there are 12 tza ligands and 18 aqua ligands participating in coordination to the metal atoms. Every tza ligand bridges a GdIII atom (Gd−O 2.384(6)−2.427(4) Å) and a CuII atom (Cu−O 2.317(4)−2.373(6) Å) through its μ-carboxylate-O,O‘ group. In the cage of the Cu12Gd6 core, there is half a Cl- and half a disordered NO3 - anion.

elements.content: In the rhombic dinuclear, μ-OH-bridged Cu2(μ-OH)2 subunit (Figure ) in 2, the CuII ion has a 4 + 2 elongated octahedral coordination environment and the equatorial positions are occupied by two μ-OH groups (Cu−O 1.942(4) Å) and two tza nitrogen atoms (Cu−N 1.979(5) Å), while the two axial positions are weakly ligated by two tza nitrogen atoms (Cu−N 2.574(4) Å). Within each dinuclear subunits, the Cu−O−Cu bridging angle is at 95.2(2)° with the intradimer Cu···Cu separation of 2.868(2) Å. Such Cu2(μ-OH)2 subunits are important in interlinkage of the Cu12Gd6 subunits. Each Cu12Gd6 cluster, acting as a four-connected node, is linked to four Cu2(OH)2 subunits by tza ligands; in turn, each Cu2(OH)2 subunit is bound to two neighboring Cu12Gd6 units in a linear arrangement. Hence the tza ligand acts as an organic bridge to link two kinds of cluster subunits (Figure ). By this way, a 2D (4,4) square net with the unit size of 20.396(2) × 20.396(2) Å and cavity size of ca. 13.7 × 13.7 Å is generated with the Cu2(OH)2(tza)4 fragment regarded as a metallolinker. Unfortunately, the layers are stacked along the c-axis in an ABAB sequence with the lattice water molecules located within and between the layers, excluding the formation of a porous structure in the solid.

elements.content: Magnetic Properties. The variable-temperature magnetic susceptibility data for the four complexes were measured in the temperature range 2−300 K in an applied magnetic field of 10 kG (Figure ), while those of 1·Gd and 2·Gd in an applied magnetic field of 1.0 kG are basically the same as the corresponding curves measured in an applied magnetic field of 10 kG. For 1·Gd, the value of χM T is 8.4 cm3 K mol-1 at 300 K and remains practically constant to 11 K. On further lowering of the temperature, χM T decreases more rapidly and equals 5.90 cm3 K mol-1 at 2 K. For 1·Nd, the value of χM T is 1.9 cm3 K mol-1 at 300 K and decreases continuously to a value of 0.87 cm3 K mol-1. The χM T values of 1 at high temperature are very close to the values calculated on the basis of the free-ion approximation for LnIII and CuII, indicating no strong magnetic exchange interaction between adjacent LnIII ions and CuII ions. For 1·Gd, the data over the whole temperature range 2−300 K are well fitted to the Curie−Weiss law with C = 8.39 and ϑ = −0.79 K; such behavior can be referred to the presence of a very weak antiferromagnetic interaction between CuII and GdIII ions. Taking into consideration the occurrence of intramolecular magnetic interactions (J) and intermolecular interactions (J‘), we tried to fit the experimental data for 1·Gd using the literature expression, leading to the following set of parameters:  g Gd = 1.99(2), g Cu = 2.03(1); J = −0.37(1) cm-1, J‘ = −0.012(6) cm-1; agreement factor R = 1.8 × 10-5 (Figure ). This fitting indicates a weak, intramolecular Cu−Gd antiferromagnetic interaction. For 1·Nd, the data in the range 35−300 K can be fitted to the Curie−Weiss law with C = 2.08 and ϑ = −27.28 K. Such decrease of χM T should mainly be in fact due to crystal-field effects around the NdIII ion, similar to those reported previously. It is well-known that the depopulation of the Nd Stark levels as temperature decreases is a distinct magnetic phenomenon. The 4I9/2 free-ion ground state in the crystal field is split into five Kramers doublets. At room temperature those doublets are equally populated; as the temperature decreases, the Kramers doublets of higher energy are successively depopulated, and the magnetic behavior significantly deviates from the Curie law predicted by the free-ion approximation.

elements.content: The χM T values are 52.41 and 14.45 cm3 K mol-1 for 2·Gd and 2·Nd at room temperature, respectively, close to the expected values of 52.52 and 15.07 cm3 K mol-1 for noninteracting metal ions. The χM T value of 2·Gd changes gradually from 52.41 cm3 K mol-1 at 300 K to 49.00 cm3 K mol-1 at 14 K, whereupon there is a more significant decrease to 33.56 cm3 K mol-1 at 2.0 K. The data in the full measured temperature range 2−300 K are well fitted to the Curie−Weiss law with C = 52.91 and ϑ = −1.13 K, indicating very weak antiferromagnetic interactions. Differently, the χM T value of 2·Nd decreases continuously on lowering the temperature, reaching a minimum value of 4.68 cm3 K mol-1 at 2 K; the data in the range 60−300 K can be fitted to the Curie−Weiss law with C = 16.86 and ϑ = −69.34 K. Such overall antiferromagnetic behavior may be mainly attributed to antiferromagnetic interactions between CuII−CuII ion pairs, as well as the crystal-field effects around the NdIII ion. In 2·Gd, there are Cu−Cu and Cu−Gd interactions in Cu12Gd6 clusters. Furthermore, such Cu12Gd6 clusters are interconnected by dinuclear Cu2(OH)2 units. These interactions are too complicated for a detailed analysis; however, they cooperatively induce an observed antiferromagnetic behavior.

Discussion

Crystallizations of 1 and 2 at different conditions demonstrate that acidity of the reaction system is critically important in the formation of the final structure; a subtle change in acidity of the reaction solution can cause a drastic change in the structure of the product. In the current case, dinuclear 1⋅Gd and 1⋅Nd can be formed at a low pH value of ca. 3.5, whereas, at higher pH value (pH ≥ 6.5), hydroxide anions may participate in coordination to form the octadecanuclear Cu12Ln6 cores. Such phenomenon is parallel to our previous observations. On the other hand, the pH is  slightly high in the syntheses of both 1 and 2 compared to those reported previously, which may be attributed to the difference between the carboxylate ligands. It is also worthy of note that upon changing of the ratio of the starting reagents, different heterometallic complexes may also be obtained, though further investigation is required.

elements.content: In this work, Htza ligand was chosen as the carboxylate source for the formation of octadecanuclear Cu12Ln6 cores as well as for the further ligation using the tetrazole group to another metal center, leading to a polymeric structure based on the Cu12Ln6 cores. This ideal is realized with the formation of the dinuclear CuII 2 subunits between the Cu12Ln6 cores, furnishing the 2D networks of 2 with the high-nuclearity nodes. Although the approach of assembling large polynuclear metal clusters into novel framework materials is still underdeveloped, a series of very recent examples of high-nuclearity 3d−4f heterometallic clusters as nodes for the construction of supramolecular networks are uncovered. In these reports, different molecular designs and synthetic approaches were employed, leading to the interesting, high-nuclearity [Ln6Cu24] octahedral-like clusters acting as the nodes and mononuclear [Cu(AA)2] (AA = amino acids) as the linkers, being different from the Cu12Ln6 cores and dinuclear CuII 2 subunits in 2, respectively.

Although the approach of assembling large polynuclear metal clusters into novel framework materials is still underdeveloped, a series of very recent examples of high-nuclearity 3d-4f heterometallic clusters as nodes for the construction of supramolecular networks are uncovered. In these reports, different molecular designs and synthetic approaches were employed, leading to the interesting, high-nuclearity [Ln6Cu24] octahedral-like clusters acting as the nodes and mononuclear [Cu(AA)2] (AA = amino acids) as the linkers, being different from the Cu12Ln6 cores and dinuclear CuII 2 subunits in 2, respectively.

elements.content: The magnetic behaviors of 1·Gd and 2·Gd are weakly overall antiferromagnetic, being similar to those reported for the Cu−Gd complexes of betaines. In contrast, ferromagnetic interactions were found for Cu−Gd complexes of oxamates, whereas the magnetic interaction in dinuclear Cu−Gd complexes made with compartmental Schiff base ligands is ferromagnetic in the large majority of published examples while an antiferromagnetic interaction is observed only in a few complexes. Although we cannot explain fairly such a difference, one reasonable conclusion is that the weak magnetic interaction between CuII and LnIII should be presented in a hydroxy-/carboxylate-bridged CuII−LnIII system.

elements.content: A new synthetic route was devised for constructing heterometallic high-nuclearity clusters into beautiful 2-D coordination architectures consisting of both octadecanuclear 3d−4f cores and dinuclear CuII cores that are interlinked by tza ligands. Our magnetic study suggests that there exist weak exchange interactions between the CuII and LnIII ions with carboxylate and hydroxy bridges. On the other hand, the formation of the 2-D networks implies that, upon a suitable assembly approach, 3-D frameworks with large pores may be constructed with the high-nuclearity 3d−4f clusters, which may be of potential applications in absorption and catalysis. We are working toward related 3-D networks based on the nanosized clusters.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusion

A new synthetic route was devised for constructing heterometallic high-nuclearity clusters into beautiful 2-D coordination architectures consisting of both octadecanuclear 3d-4f cores and dinuclear CuII cores that are interlinked by tza ligands. Our magnetic study suggests that there exist weak exchange interactions between the CuII and LnIII ions with carboxylate and hydroxy bridges. On the other hand, the formation of the 2-D networks implies that, upon a suitable assembly approach, 3-D frameworks with large pores may be constructed with the high-nuclearity 3d-4f clusters, which may be of potential applications in absorption and catalysis. We are working toward related 3-D networks based on the nanosized clusters.

Preparation. CuGd(tza) 4 (H 2 O) 5 Cl (1 · Gd). A mixture of Htza (0.256 g, 2.0 mmol) and CuCl2·2H2O (0.170 g, 1.0 mmol) was dissolved in distilled water (5 mL), and the solution was heated at 60 °C for 10 min; Gd(NO)3·5H2O (0.433 g, 1.0 mmol) was then added.
